At 15:11 11/10/2005, you wrote:
&gt;Hi Ian,
&gt;
&gt;Many game developers do publish papers nowadays. I guess the AAAI
&gt;&quot;Challenges in Game AI Workshop&quot; gets the most submissions (and is the
&gt;most relevant to modern day computer game dev) but there is also the
&gt;IEEE CIG symposium, which is of interest. I&#39;m sure there are others.

Hi,
         Yes I know there is more of this now, I was even on the 
program committee for CIG 2005.

         Since I no longer work in that industry it&#39;s no longer relevant.

         I was just illustrating the point with an account from a few 
years ago.

         Ian

&gt;Here&#39;s are a couple of links for you
&gt;
&gt;http://csapps.essex.ac.uk/cig/
&gt;
&gt;http://www.simbionic.com/gameai/schedule.html
&gt;
&gt;Regards
&gt;
&gt;Mat Buckland
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;-----Original Message-----
&gt;From: neat@yahoogroups.com [mailto:neat@yahoogroups.com] On Behalf Of
&gt;Ian Badcoe
&gt;Sent: Tuesday, October 11, 2005 3:01 PM
&gt;To: neat@yahoogroups.com
&gt;Subject: [neat] Publish and be damned?
&gt;
&gt;Hi,
&gt;         I experiment with NEAT purely because I enjoy it, and I think
&gt;there
&gt;is some good progress to be made on a reasonable time-frame.
&gt;
&gt;         And for the purposes of that, there is no need for me to do
&gt;anything
&gt;more than write the odd web-page (very odd, in all probability :) and
&gt;post things here.
&gt;
&gt;         BUT, with half an eye on the future, I might want to get back
&gt;into
&gt;academia one day (say if its raining and I happen to be passing a
&gt;university), and to do that, you really do have to have a
&gt;track-record of publications you can point at.  I know this to be a
&gt;particularly acute problem (at least here in the UK) because I tried
&gt;it a few years ago and, even explaining that I hadn&#39;t published
&gt;anything because the games industry is paranoid and _never_ publishes
&gt;anything (this 99.5% true) I still couldn&#39;t get them to rate me.
&gt;
&gt;         SO, I&#39;d quite like to publish some of my current work (when it
&gt;gets
&gt;results that is, but the reason I mention this now is that at the
&gt;moment its looking very promising).  And I was wondering what people
&gt;thought the prospects are.  I mean, do journals generally have a rule
&gt;that says you have to be a member of a university before they&#39;ll look
&gt;at your work?  I&#39;m guessing not because, of course, many corporate
&gt;R&D depts also regularly publish.  But what are the prospects for an
&gt;unknown individual?  Would your submission get the same treatment as
&gt;anybody&#39;s?  Or would they throw it on a &quot;possible loonies&quot; pile and
&gt;forget about it?
&gt;
&gt;         Would I need somebody in a university to &quot;front&quot; it for me --
&gt;e.g.
&gt;list themselves as the corresponding author and me as the co-author
&gt;of the work?  If that&#39;s the case, I would be quite open to the idea,
&gt;I mean it even seems reasonably honest, not really different from
&gt;putting your laboratory head on your papers because he provided the
&gt;environment in which the work happened (even if he actually
&gt;understand nothing of your work -- this used to happen in
&gt;biochemistry, mentioning no names...).
&gt;
&gt;         Opinions?
&gt;
&gt;         Ian
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;In fifteen minutes, everybody will be in the future.
